An American, two kinds of citizens.
New York — at the time I was writing this article, officials across the United States were still tabulating votes from the 2020 U.S. presidential election.
Recounts and legal challenges are likely to follow once the final tally is confirmed.
This is expected in such a fiercely competitive election with a record-high voter turnout.
Only U.S. citizens can vote in the election of the U.S. president, but this choice affects people in many places.
If it's premature to confirm the election outcome now, then it's hardly too early to explore the lessons this election holds for the world's most powerful nation.
From a positive perspective, the United States remains a powerful democratic nation.
Despite being subject to actual restrictions related to the pandemic, voter turnout remains high.
This process appears to be unfolding as planned.
Violent incidents are rare.
Courts are investigating decisions by the United States Postal Service that appear to be politically motivated, impeding the delivery of ballots from areas expected to vote mainly for the Democratic Party.
President Trump's baseless claim of victory on Tuesday evening drew little reaction, while his call to stop counting votes (at least in the states where he was leading) seemed to fall on deaf ears.
However, the significant divisions among U.S. voters remain a concern.
The two candidates' votes are almost equal.
It's hardly surprising that such divisions could lead to a divided government.
If current trends continue, the Democratic Party will win the White House and retain control of the House of Representatives, while the Republican Party will continue to control the Senate.
Governors' and state legislative seats are almost evenly divided between the two parties, with a slight edge for the Republican Party.
The Democratic Party's anticipated "blue wave" failed to materialize.
Joe Biden is likely to win the popular vote by a large margin, probably securing four to five million votes out of nearly 160 million cast.
But Republican Party members held onto many seats that many had predicted they would flip in the Senate, while the Democratic Party actually lost seats in the House of Representatives.
This result stems from no strong mandate, nor is it a result of any political realignment.
President Trump's poll situation was very good, gaining 50 million more votes than in 2016, making him the second-most voted candidate in U.S. presidential election history, and surpassing any previous winner.
Notably, this occurred amidst a backdrop of record-breaking daily COVID-19 cases and deaths, with over 100,000 new cases and 1,000-plus fatalities reported each day.
Just as the consequences of his government's mishandling of the pandemic became most dire, nearly half of the voters shifted their support to him.
Even if Trump loses, which seems quite likely, he will still wield significant influence, particularly if he remains in the public eye, which also appears plausible.
Even if he himself does not run, he is likely to exert considerable influence on the Republican Party's choice of nominee in the 2024 presidential election.
The Republican Party would be far removed from the party of former President George H.W. Bush or Ronald Reagan.
Trumpism — a modern American populism — will still be a powerful force.
Not unexpectedly, despite lacking any evidence, Trump has been vigorously attempting to portray himself as virtuous and upright, and has been trying to delegitimize the election results and accuse electoral irregularities.
His many supporters would refuse to accept the legitimacy of Joe Biden as President.
Trump is likely to never concede defeat, let alone attend the swearing-in ceremony of his successor.
As Will Rogers once said, Trump has never met a norm he couldn't break.
The American people are increasingly living in different worlds.
They would categorize themselves into separate communities and regions based on their similar viewpoints.
Each world tends to watch its own cable TV channels, listen to its own radio stations and podcasts, and visit its own websites.
The absence of a national civics curriculum has facilitated the segmentation of different age groups.
It is worth noting that national divisions are often not drawn along economic lines in most cases.
Each layer of society cast their votes for the two candidates, and the voting patterns by population, gender, and race did not turn out to be one-sided as many people had predicted.
Their disagreement mainly lies in the remedy.
Education levels are clearly an indicator of political orientation, as are geographical locations. Republican voters tend to reside in rural and suburban areas, while Democratic voters tend to reside in urban areas.
However, the influence of culture on American politics may be greater than any other factor.
In fact, foreign policy seems to be of little importance in the campaign, except for mobilizing specific constituencies, such as the large Cuban and Venezuelan communities in southern Florida.
In such a backdrop, it is difficult to garner public support for major reform of the presidential election process or the way the government operates.
This situation is no different from the reform of the United Nations Security Council.
Many people believe that the current system has severe flaws and lacks representation, but it is impossible to reach a consensus on reform because any potential solution would benefit some while harming others.
It is no surprise that those who would be harmed by change will resist it.
This will make governance more challenging.
This is largely dependent on Senate Republican leader Mitch McConnell's assessment, as well as his ability and willingness to work with and cooperate with future President Biden.
Working with Mitch McConnell to pass legislation would also require President Biden to make concessions, which would undoubtedly be met with resistance from his own party's more ideologically driven members.
Democratic Party members have tried to sharply deny everything related to Trump and his supporters.
However, they were unsuccessful.
While Republican Party members are seeking an election that will validate Trump.
However, they were unsuccessful.
On the contrary, the election reveals a nation and two kinds of citizens.
They will have to coexist; but whether they can coexist, remains to be seen.
